### how the first level caching works
The JPA first-level cache, also known as the Persistence Context, is automatically enabled and mandatory for every EntityManager.  It acts as a session-scoped cache that stores managed entity instances within the current transaction, ensuring that only one instance of a specific entity with a given ID exists in memory at any time.

How it operates:

When an entity is loaded via find() or persist(), it is stored in an internal HashMap (the cache) keyed by the entity name and identifier.
Subsequent requests for the same entity within the same transaction retrieve the object directly from this cache rather than executing a new SQL query.
The cache guarantees application-level repeatable reads, meaning modifications made to an entity (e.g., o.setComment("hello")) are immediately visible to all references of that entity within the transaction.
Lifecycle and Scope:

The cache is bound to the current Hibernate Session (or EntityManager) and exists only for the duration of the transaction.
It is not shared between different transactions or EntityManager instances; a new transaction starts with a fresh, empty cache.
The cache is automatically cleared when the transaction commits, rolls back, or the EntityManager is closed.
Developers can manually clear the cache using EntityManager.clear() or refresh a specific entity using EntityManager.refresh().
Key Benefits:

Performance: Significantly reduces database load by preventing repeated SQL queries for the same entity within a single unit of work.
Data Consistency: Ensures that all code within the transaction sees the same, updated state of an entity.
Transaction Management: Works seamlessly with @Transactional annotations, where each method in a separate transaction gets its own isolated cache.


