1. How Indexes Work in the DB
   Think of a database index exactly like the index at the back of a book.

Without an index (Table Scan): If you want to find a specific topic in a book and there is no index, you have to read every single page from the beginning until you find it. In a database, this is called a Full Table Scan, which is very slow if your table has millions of rows.
With an index: You look up the topic in the index, see the exact page number, and jump straight to it.
Under the hood: Databases typically use data structures like B-Trees (Balanced Trees) or Hash Tables to store indexes. When you index a column (e.g., email), the database stores the email values in a sorted tree structure along with a pointer to the physical memory location of the entire row.
The Trade-off: Indexes drastically speed up SELECT (read) queries, but they slow down INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE (write) operations because the database has to update the index tree every time the data changes. They also take up extra disk space.

3. Benefits of Using @Table to Create Indexes
   Automated Schema Generation: If you are using Hibernate's hbm2ddl.auto (e.g., update or create), Hibernate will automatically generate the CREATE INDEX SQL statements and apply them to your database. You don't have to write manual SQL scripts.
   Code as Documentation: Any developer looking at the Employee entity immediately knows which columns are optimized for querying. The database schema logic remains tightly coupled with the Java code, acting as a single source of truth.
   Optimized Queries: Defining composite indexes (last_name, first_name) natively translates to the DB, heavily optimizing queries like findByLastNameAndFirstName(String last, String first).
   Environment Consistency: It ensures that every time the app is spun up on a new environment (like a local H2 in-memory DB for testing), the indexes are created, ensuring your tests behave similarly to production.


