### column field
  - its optional jpa will add this automatically with the default values
    The @Column annotation allows you to map a Java field directly to a specific column in a database table and define exactly how that column should behave. While it is optional (JPA will just use the Java variable name and default settings if omitted), it is highly recommended to use it for explicit schema definition.

Here are the most commonly used properties inside @Column:

1. name Defines the exact name of the column in the database.

Default: The name of the Java variable (Spring Boot usually converts camelCase to snake_case automatically, so firstName becomes first_name).
Example: @Column(name = "user_email_address")
2. unique A boolean that specifies whether this single column should have a unique constraint.

Default: false
Note: This is a shorthand for single-column constraints. If you need a composite unique constraint (covering 2 or more columns together), you must use @Table(uniqueConstraints = ...) instead.
Example: @Column(unique = true)
3. nullable A boolean that specifies if the database column allows NULL values.

Default: true
Note: Setting it to false automatically generates a NOT NULL constraint in the database. It is best practice to set nullable = false for required fields.
Example: @Column(nullable = false)
4. length Specifies the maximum character length of the column. This is primarily used for String variables.

Default: 255
Note: It defines the VARCHAR(length) in the database. If you try to save a string longer than this, the database will throw a data truncation error.
Example: @Column(length = 50)
5. updatable A boolean that tells JPA whether this column should be included in generated UPDATE SQL statements.

Default: true
Note: If set to false, once the entity is created, JPA will ignore any changes to this field during subsequent saves. This is extremely useful for audit fields like created_at or created_by that should never change after the initial insert.
Example: @Column(updatable = false)
6. insertable A boolean that tells JPA whether this column should be included in generated INSERT SQL statements.

Default: true
Note: If set to false, JPA will ignore this field when creating a new row. Typically used when the database itself generates the value (e.g., via a DB trigger or a default value).
Example: @Column(insertable = false)
7. columnDefinition Allows you to provide a raw SQL fragment that is used when generating the DDL (Data Definition Language) for the column.

Default: Empty
Note: Extremely useful when you need a specific database type that JPA doesn't map to easily (like TEXT or JSONB in Postgres, or explicit default values).
Example: @Column(columnDefinition = "VARCHAR(255) DEFAULT 'PENDING'") or @Column(columnDefinition = "TEXT")

What is a Sequence?
In a database (like PostgreSQL, Oracle, or SQL Server), a Sequence is an independent database object that generates a sequence of numeric values. Unlike an AUTO_INCREMENT or IDENTITY column which is hard-tied to one specific table, a sequence exists on its own. You ask the database for the "next value" from the sequence, and it hands you a number, guaranteeing that it won't give that exact number to any other transaction.

How does GenerationType.SEQUENCE work in JPA?
When you use the sequence strategy, Hibernate asks the database sequence for the next available ID before it actually executes the INSERT statement.

To use it effectively, you typically pair @GeneratedValue with the @SequenceGenerator annotation so you can customize how it behaves.

```java
import jakarta.persistence.Entity;
import jakarta.persistence.Id;
import jakarta.persistence.GeneratedValue;
import jakarta.persistence.GenerationType;
import jakarta.persistence.SequenceGenerator;

@Entity
public class Employee {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.SEQUENCE, generator = "emp_generator")
    @SequenceGenerator(
        name = "emp_generator",              // The name referenced in @GeneratedValue
        sequenceName = "employee_id_seq",    // The actual name of the sequence in the Database
        initialValue = 1000,                 // Start generating IDs from 1000
        allocationSize = 50                  // How many IDs Hibernate pre-fetches at once (Crucial!)
    )
    /*
            name - its unique name , internal for JPA, we can use it in different entity
            sequeneName - its name which is created in DB. or if you have manually created sequence in DB, then use that name here 
            initialValue: sequence no starts from here
            allocationSize : cache data , hibernate prefetch this much ids before hand , so that it will not query DB again and again 
     */
    private Long id;

    // other fields...
}

```
Why use SEQUENCE over IDENTITY? (The Performance Benefit)
The biggest advantage of SEQUENCE over GenerationType.IDENTITY (which maps to MySQL's AUTO_INCREMENT) is Batch Insertion.

The problem with IDENTITY: If you want to save 100 Employee objects at once, Hibernate has to execute 100 separate INSERT statements immediately. Why? Because the only way the database will generate the ID is if the row is physically inserted. Hibernate needs that ID to manage the entity, so it cannot group the inserts together.
The magic of SEQUENCE and allocationSize: Notice allocationSize = 50 in the example above. When Hibernate needs an ID to save a new Employee, it calls the database sequence once and asks for 50 IDs upfront. The database sequence jumps its internal counter by 50 and gives Hibernate a block of IDs to use. Now, Hibernate holds these 50 IDs in memory. It can assign them to 50 Employee objects and then send a single, highly-optimized Batch INSERT statement to the database containing all 50 rows at once. This drastically reduces network round-trips and speeds up bulk inserts.
Summary
If your underlying database supports sequences (like PostgreSQL, Oracle, or modern SQL Server), GenerationType.SEQUENCE is highly recommended over IDENTITY because it decouples ID generation from row insertion, enabling massive performance optimizations through JDBC batching. (Note: MySQL historically did not support true sequences, forcing developers to use IDENTITY or TABLE generation, though newer versions have introduced sequence support).


